<dl id="n10009f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10009f">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10009f"> 9(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bookshrines</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">So far as literature and art are concerned, the period of the Viking occupation is one of the most interesting in the history of Ireland. In spite of the destruction of the monasteries and the departure of most of the monks to the Continent <font color="green">[fugitives, e.g., to the monastery of St. Gall, Switzerland]</font> the work of the great schools was carried on &hellip; cumhdachs, or <mark>book-shrines</mark> of plated gold and silver, were made for the three great manuscripts, the <cite>Book of Kells</cite>, the <cite>Book of Durrow</cite> and the <cite>Book of Armagh</cite> &hellip;. <small> A. WALSH, <a name="AWSR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AWSR"><cite title="source">Scandinavian Relations with Ireland During the Viking Period</cite></a> (1922) 19</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <cite>FW</cite> 559.07 is not from this notebook. </mm> </dd></dl>
